{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HCfp8hafbPwR2UMF6fFarB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still getting `createUser requires authentication`. The socket connection also doesn't bypass auth.\n\nOK I'm going to take the invasive approach. Let me properly understand the data persistence situation:\n- mongodb-replica-1 (primary) has PVC `mongodb-data-mongodb-replica-1`\n- The admin user is in the admin database on this PVC\n\nMy plan:\n1. Modify the mongod ConfigMap to disable authorization (keep everything else, remove `authorization: enabled` and remove `keyFile`)\n2. Delete mongodb-replica-1 pod (it will restart with the new config)\n3. When it comes up without auth, connect and create the monitoring user\n4. Restore the ConfigMap\n5. Delete the pod again so it restarts with auth\n\nThe downside is the replica set will lose the primary temporarily and the members won't sync properly during the auth-disabled window since they expect keyfile auth, so the set may degrade but should recover.\n\nActually, this is quite risky. Let me think of a less disruptive approach instead. I could try using `mongod --setParameter` to bypass auth, but that won't work via external calls. Or I could create a temporary pod that mounts the same volume but with a modified ConfigMap that disables auth.\n\nBut here's the problem: the PVC is ReadWriteOnce, so I'd need to scale down the secondary pod first to free up the volume. If I scale down one secondary, the replica set drops to two members, which still maintains a majority with three total members. So I could scale down mongodb-replica-2, spin up a temporary pod using its PVC to create the monitoring user without auth, then scale the secondary back up. The catch is that users in the admin database are replicated across all members, so creating a user on one member's data should propagate to the primary—but only if I'm actually writing to the replica set's data, not running standalone. So if I restart the secondary as a replica set member, it'll sync with the primary and any user I created in standalone mode gets wiped out if the primary doesn't have it. The real solution is to modify the user on the primary's data directly in standalone mode. Actually, there's a simpler approach: I could temporarily disable authorization on just the primary pod, restart it, create the user, then re-enable auth.\n\nBut there's a problem with this approach—the other replica set members still have keyfile authentication enabled, and they won't be able to authenticate with a primary that no longer requires auth, which could break replication.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The real issue is why the credentials are failing in the first place. Let me reconsider—maybe the admin user was created in the `local` database instead of `admin`, or perhaps I need to try the `SCRAM-SHA-1` authentication mechanism explicitly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":274,"cache_read_input_tokens":54791,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":274},"output_tokens":32,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9ffc1fd8-3221-4ea3-9d50-784bafcd3a01","uuid":"f12700f3-dfae-4b4f-bbb8-04bb0395c1d8","request_id":"req_011CcggVAShwsKEUaCuy1xK7"}
